SIMPLE: exposure
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exposure
<hw>Ex*po"sure</hw> <pr>(?;135)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Expose</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of exposing or laying
open, setting forth, laying bare of protection, depriving of care or
concealment, or setting out to reprobation or contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>exposure</qex> of Fuller . . . put an end to the
practices of that vile tribe.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being exposed or laid open or bare;
openness to danger; accessibility to anything that may affect,
especially detrimentally; <as>as, <ex>exposure</ex> to observation, to
cold, to inconvenience</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When we have our naked frailties hid,⟦br⟧
That suffer in <qex>exposure</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Position as to points of compass, or to influences
of climate, etc.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Under a southern
<xex>exposure</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The best <qex>exposure</qex> of the two for woodcocks.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir. W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>The exposing of a sensitized
plate to the action of light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Expound</ent>⟦br⟧
